===Etymology 1===
{{bor|en|frm|masque||a covering to hide or protect the face}}, from {{der|en|it|maschera||mask, disguise}}, from {{der|en|ML.|masca}}, {{m|en|mascha}}, {{m|la|mascus||mask, nightmare, ghost}}, of uncertain origin. Replaced {{cog|ang|grīma||mask}}.

{{cog|ML.|masca}}, {{m|la|mascha}}, {{m|la|mascus}} may represent the merger of two or more words: 1). a {{cog|gem}} word from {{cog|frk|*maska}}, {{m|frk|*maskra|mask, mesh}} (compare {{cog|ang|mæscre||mesh; discoloration, spot}}, {{m|ang|masc||net, mesh netting}}; {{cog|goh|māsca||mesh, ties}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*maskwǭ||mesh, mask}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mezgʷ-||to knit, twist}}, from the practice of wearing mesh netting over the face as a mask to filter air, keeping soot and dust particles from entering the lungs (compare {{m|en|surgical mask}}, {{m|en|gas mask}}, etc.); 2). {{cog|fro|mascurer}} {{gloss|"to blacken (the face)"; compare {{cog|oc|mascarar}}, {{cog|ca|mascarar}}, {{cog|wa|maxhurer}}}}, from a stem {{m|und|*maska}}, {{m|und|*mask-||black}} believed to be of Pre-Indo-European origin giving rise to words meaning "witch, wizard, sorcerer" (compare {{cog|pro|masco||witch}}, {{cog|oc|masca||witch}}, {{cog|fr|masque||brothel-keeper, witch}}); and perhaps another 3). from {{cog|ar|مَسْخَرَة||buffoon, fool, pleasantry, anything ridiculous}}, from {{m|ar|سَخِرَة||to ridicule, to laugh at}}.

* Derived from the ''-r-'' form: {{cog|it|maschera}}, {{cog|es|-}} and {{cog|pt|máscara}}, {{cog|nl|masker}}, {{cog|en|masquerade}}.
* Derived from the form lacking ''-r-'': {{cog|de|Maske}} and {{cog|sv|mask}}.<ref>{{R:EWddS|ed=22}}</ref>

